add(PLANT, "03_Leaf_Anatomy_and_Gas_Exchange.txt", "LEAF ANATOMY AND GAS EXCHANGE", "An illustrated guide to leaf layers, stomata, guard cells, photosynthesis, transpiration and plant water balance", "* Cuticle light green\n* Epidermis pale yellow\n* Palisade mesophyll emerald\n* Spongy mesophyll lime\n* Stomata blue\n* Guard cells teal\n* Xylem cyan\n* Phloem orange", "* Cuticle\n* Upper epidermis\n* Palisade mesophyll\n* Spongy mesophyll\n* Air spaces\n* Lower epidermis\n* Stomata\n* Guard cells\n* Vein\n* Xylem\n* Phloem\n* Chloroplasts", "* Leaf cross-section\n* Stomatal opening and closing\n* Gas exchange\n* Transpiration\n* Photosynthesis location\n* Guard-cell turgor\n* Leaf adaptations\n* Sun versus shade leaves\n* Water stress response", "* Carbon dioxide enters through stomata\n* Oxygen exits through stomata\n* Water vapour diffuses out\n* Guard cells regulate pore size\n* Xylem supplies water\n* Mesophyll cells photosynthesise\n* Phloem transports sugars", "* Drought stress\n* Wilting\n* Transpiration cooling\n* Crop water management\n* Leaf disease signs\n* Climate and stomatal conductance", "Use a leaf cross-section as the hero, with stomatal guard-cell close-up and gas arrows as major visual elements.", "* Do not show stomata only on the top surface for all plants\n* Photosynthesis occurs mainly in chloroplast-rich mesophyll\n* Transpiration is water vapour loss, not liquid dripping\n* Guard cells control opening by turgor changes\n* Leaf adaptations vary by species")
add(PLANT, "04_Plant_Reproduction_and_Pollination.txt", "PLANT REPRODUCTION AND POLLINATION", "An illustrated guide to flowers, pollen, ovules, fertilization, seeds, fruits and pollinator relationships", "* Petals pink\n* Sepals green\n* Anthers yellow\n* Pollen gold\n* Stigma purple\n* Ovary teal\n* Ovules blue\n* Pollinators orange", "* Petal\n* Sepal\n* Stamen\n* Anther\n* Filament\n* Pollen grain\n* Carpel\n* Stigma\n* Style\n* Ovary\n* Ovule\n* Nectar guide\n* Seed\n* Fruit", "* Flower anatomy\n* Pollination types\n* Animal and wind pollination\n* Pollen tube growth\n* Double fertilization\n* Seed formation\n* Fruit development\n* Seed dispersal\n* Pollinator coevolution\n* Reproductive diversity", "* Pollen reaches stigma\n* Pollen grain germinates\n* Pollen tube grows down style\n* Sperm cells reach ovule\n* Double fertilization occurs\n* Embryo and endosperm form\n* Ovule becomes seed\n* Ovary develops into fruit", "* Pollinator decline\n* Crop pollination\n* Allergies to pollen\n* Hybridization\n* Seed saving\n* Habitat conservation", "Use a large flower cutaway centrally, pollen tube sequence right and pollinator/seed dispersal panels along bottom.", "* Do not show seed plants needing water for sperm to swim like mosses/ferns\n* Double fertilization is characteristic of flowering plants\n* Not all flowers require animal pollinators\n* Fruit develops from ovary tissue in botanical terms\n* Avoid oversimplifying pollinator relationships")
add(PLANT, "05_Seed_Germination_and_Plant_Growth.txt", "SEED GERMINATION AND PLANT GROWTH", "An illustrated guide to seed structure, dormancy, germination triggers, seedling development, hormones and growth responses", "* Seed coat brown\n* Embryo green\n* Endosperm cream\n* Water blue\n* Radicle gold\n* Shoot emerald\n* Auxin purple\n* Light yellow", "* Seed coat\n* Embryo\n* Cotyledon\n* Endosperm\n* Radicle\n* Plumule\n* Hypocotyl\n* Epicotyl\n* Root hairs\n* Shoot tip\n* Apical meristem\n* First leaves", "* Seed structure\n* Dormancy\n* Imbibition\n* Enzyme activation\n* Germination requirements\n* Seedling establishment\n* Phototropism\n* Gravitropism\n* Auxin role\n* Primary growth", "* Dry seed absorbs water\n* Metabolism restarts\n* Enzymes mobilise stored food\n* Radicle emerges first\n* Shoot grows upward\n* Cotyledons support early growth\n* Leaves expand\n* Photosynthesis supports independent growth", "* Crop germination\n* Seed storage\n* Soil temperature and moisture\n* Seedling disease\n* Plant hormones\n* Agriculture and restoration ecology", "Use a time-lapse germination sequence across the centre with seed anatomy enlarged at left.", "* Germination requirements vary by species\n* Radicle usually emerges before shoot\n* Seeds do not need light universally\n* Stored food may be in endosperm or cotyledons depending on species\n* Avoid implying growth is only cell enlargement")
add(PLANT, "06_Plant_Hormones_and_Tropisms.txt", "PLANT HORMONES AND TROPISMS", "An illustrated guide to auxin, gibberellins, cytokinins, abscisic acid, ethylene and plant responses to the environment", "* Auxin purple\n* Gibberellin green\n* Cytokinin blue\n* ABA orange\n* Ethylene red\n* Light yellow\n* Gravity teal\n* Growth arrows gold", "* Shoot tip\n* Root tip\n* Apical meristem\n* Lateral bud\n* Growing stem\n* Fruit\n* Stomata\n* Seed\n* Hormone gradients\n* Directional light\n* Gravity vector", "* Major plant hormones\n* Phototropism\n* Gravitropism\n* Thigmotropism\n* Apical dominance\n* Seed dormancy\n* Fruit ripening\n* Stomatal responses\n* Stress responses\n* Agricultural hormone applications", "* Light direction is detected\n* Auxin distribution changes\n* Cells elongate unevenly\n* Shoot bends toward light\n* Roots respond differently to gravity\n* Hormones integrate environmental signals\n* Growth pattern changes over time", "* Fruit ripening control\n* Rooting powders\n* Weed control concepts\n* Drought response\n* Seed dormancy management\n* Greenhouse production", "Use a plant bending toward light centrally, with hormone icons and tropism mini-panels around it.", "* Plant hormones act in networks, not isolated single effects\n* Auxin effects differ by tissue and concentration\n* Do not show plants moving by muscles\n* Ethylene is a gas hormone\n* Avoid saying plants intentionally choose growth direction")
add(PLANT, "07_Plant_Defense_and_Immunity.txt", "PLANT DEFENSE AND IMMUNITY", "An illustrated guide to physical barriers, chemical defenses, pathogen recognition, hypersensitive response and systemic acquired resistance", "* Cuticle green\n* Cell wall brown\n* Pathogen red\n* Defense chemicals purple\n* Stomata blue\n* Immune signal gold\n* Hypersensitive response orange\n* Beneficial microbes teal", "* Cuticle\n* Cell wall\n* Stomata\n* Trichomes\n* Pathogen\n* Recognition receptor\n* Defence signalling molecules\n* Phytoalexins\n* Lignin reinforcement\n* Dead infected cell zone\n* Systemic signal\n* Beneficial rhizosphere microbes", "* Passive barriers\n* Chemical defenses\n* Pattern recognition receptors\n* Effector-triggered immunity\n* Hypersensitive response\n* Systemic acquired resistance\n* Herbivore defense\n* Symbiosis and microbiome\n* Crop disease resistance\n* Integrated pest management", "* Pathogen contacts plant surface\n* Barrier slows entry\n* Receptors detect pathogen patterns\n* Defence genes activate\n* Antimicrobial compounds accumulate\n* Cell walls reinforce\n* Local infected cells may die\n* Systemic signals prime distant tissues", "* Fungal, bacterial and viral plant diseases\n* Insect herbivory\n* Crop resistance breeding\n* Pesticide reduction strategies\n* Plant quarantine\n* Food security", "Use a leaf infection cross-section centrally, with defense layers and signalling pathway as connected panels.", "* Plants have immune systems but not antibodies like animals\n* Do not show white blood cells in plants\n* Hypersensitive response is localized cell death, not whole-plant death\n* Defense costs energy and tradeoffs exist\n* Avoid implying all microbes are harmful")
add(PLANT, "08_Plant_Transport_Xylem_and_Phloem.txt", "PLANT TRANSPORT: XYLEM AND PHLOEM", "An illustrated guide to water movement, transpiration pull, sugar transport, pressure flow and vascular tissue structure", "* Xylem blue\n* Phloem orange\n* Water cyan\n* Sugars gold\n* Leaves green\n* Roots brown\n* Stomata teal\n* Pressure arrows purple", "* Root hair\n* Xylem vessel\n* Tracheid\n* Phloem sieve tube\n* Companion cell\n* Leaf vein\n* Stomata\n* Source leaf\n* Sink root/fruit\n* Transpiration stream\n* Sugar loading zone", "* Xylem structure\n* Cohesion-tension theory\n* Transpiration pull\n* Root pressure concept\n* Phloem structure\n* Source and sink tissues\n* Pressure-flow hypothesis\n* Vascular bundles\n* Ringing/girdling concept\n* Plant water stress", "* Water enters roots\n* Xylem carries water upward\n* Transpiration creates tension\n* Cohesion and adhesion maintain water column\n* Leaves produce sugars\n* Sugars load into phloem\n* Water enters phloem osmotically\n* Pressure drives sap toward sinks", "* Wilting\n* Drought stress\n* Cavitation concept\n* Crop irrigation\n* Sap flow\n* Tree physiology\n* Fruit development as sugar sink", "Use a whole plant with blue upward xylem arrows and orange source-to-sink phloem arrows as the central visual.", "* Xylem is mostly upward water transport in vascular plants\n* Phloem can move sugars to different sinks, not only downward\n* Do not show xylem actively pumping like a heart\n* Cohesion-tension depends on transpiration\n* Keep source-sink terminology clear")
add(PLANT, "09_Plant_Kingdom_Mosses_Ferns_Gymnosperms_Angiosperms.txt", "THE PLANT KINGDOM", "An illustrated guide to mosses, ferns, gymnosperms, angiosperms, vascular tissue, seeds, flowers and evolutionary innovations", "* Mosses green\n* Ferns teal\n* Gymnosperms blue-green\n* Angiosperms pink\n* Spores gold\n* Seeds brown\n* Vascular tissue purple\n* Flowers red", "* Moss gametophyte\n* Fern frond\n* Fern sporangia\n* Conifer cone\n* Pollen grain\n* Seed\n* Flower\n* Fruit\n* Vascular tissue\n* Alternation of generations diagram", "* Bryophytes\n* Seedless vascular plants\n* Gymnosperms\n* Angiosperms\n* Spores versus seeds\n* Vascular tissue evolution\n* Pollen\n* Flowers and fruits\n* Alternation of generations\n* Adaptations to land", "* Early land plants depend on water for reproduction\n* Vascular tissue supports height and transport\n* Spores disperse\n* Seeds protect embryos\n* Pollen reduces dependence on free water\n* Flowers and fruits support pollination and dispersal\n* Plant lineages diversify", "* Conservation\n* Forestry\n* Agriculture\n* Fern and moss ecology\n* Gymnosperm forests\n* Angiosperm crop diversity", "Use a left-to-right evolutionary innovation timeline with representative plant illustrations and feature icons.", "* Evolution is branching, not a ladder of progress\n* Mosses, ferns, gymnosperms and angiosperms coexist today\n* Do not call gymnosperms flowering plants\n* Spores and seeds are different structures\n* Keep alternation of generations simplified but accurate")
add(PLANT, "10_Plant_Tissue_Culture_and_Biotechnology.txt", "PLANT TISSUE CULTURE AND BIOTECHNOLOGY", "An illustrated guide to totipotency, sterile culture, callus, micropropagation, genetic transformation and crop improvement", "* Explant green\n* Sterile medium amber\n* Callus cream\n* Shoots teal\n* Roots brown\n* Hormones purple\n* Transgene gold\n* Lab equipment blue", "* Explant\n* Sterile culture vessel\n* Nutrient medium\n* Callus\n* Shoot meristem\n* Rooted plantlet\n* Growth chamber\n* Laminar-flow hood\n* Auxin/cytokinin balance\n* Transformed cells\n* Greenhouse acclimatization", "* Totipotency\n* Aseptic technique\n* Culture media\n* Callus induction\n* Shoot and root regeneration\n* Micropropagation\n* Somatic embryogenesis\n* Genetic transformation overview\n* Marker selection\n* Acclimatization and biosafety", "* Select healthy explant\n* Surface sterilize tissue\n* Place on sterile nutrient medium\n* Cells divide into callus\n* Hormone balance induces shoots\n* Rooting medium forms roots\n* Plantlets acclimatize\n* Plants are transferred to soil", "* Disease-free propagation\n* Rare plant conservation\n* Crop improvement\n* Genetic engineering research\n* Clonal uniformity risks\n* Contamination control\n* Regulatory oversight", "Use a lab workflow from explant to plantlet as the main timeline, with callus and hormone panels enlarged.", "* Tissue culture requires sterile technique\n* Totipotency does not mean every cell always regenerates easily\n* Genetic modification is not the same as ordinary micropropagation\n* Avoid overstating GMO benefits or risks\n* Acclimatization is required before field growth")

add(ECO, "01_Ecosystems_and_Food_Webs.txt", "ECOSYSTEMS AND FOOD WEBS", "An illustrated guide to producers, consumers, decomposers, energy flow, trophic levels and ecosystem balance", "* Producers green\n* Herbivores yellow\n* Carnivores red\n* Omnivores purple\n* Decomposers brown\n* Energy arrows gold\n* Nutrient cycling blue\n* Detritus grey", "* Sun\n* Producer plants/algae\n* Primary consumer\n* Secondary consumer\n* Tertiary consumer\n* Decomposer fungi\n* Decomposer bacteria\n* Detritus\n* Food chain\n* Food web\n* Trophic pyramid", "* Ecosystem components\n* Biotic and abiotic factors\n* Producers and photosynthesis\n* Consumers\n* Decomposers\n* Trophic levels\n* Food webs versus food chains\n* Energy transfer efficiency\n* Biomass pyramid\n* Keystone species concept", "* Sunlight enters ecosystem\n* Producers capture energy\n* Herbivores eat producers\n* Predators eat consumers\n* Decomposers recycle dead matter\n* Nutrients return to soil or water\n* Energy is lost as heat at each transfer", "* Habitat change\n* Invasive species\n* Pollution\n* Overharvesting\n* Conservation biology\n* Ecosystem services\n* Restoration ecology", "Use a rich ecosystem scene with a food web overlay and a trophic pyramid inset.", "* Energy flows one way while nutrients cycle\n* Food webs are networks, not simple ladders\n* Decomposers are essential, not optional\n* Avoid implying ecosystems are always perfectly balanced\n* Keep arrows directionally clear")
add(ECO, "02_Biomes_of_the_World.txt", "BIOMES OF THE WORLD", "An illustrated guide to major terrestrial and aquatic biomes, climate patterns, adaptations, biodiversity and human impact", "* Tropical forest emerald\n* Desert orange\n* Grassland gold\n* Temperate forest green\n* Taiga blue-green\n* Tundra pale blue\n* Freshwater cyan\n* Marine navy", "* World biome map\n* Tropical rainforest\n* Desert\n* Savanna\n* Temperate grassland\n* Temperate forest\n* Boreal forest\n* Tundra\n* Freshwater lake\n* Coral reef\n* Open ocean\n* Climate graph", "* Temperature and precipitation\n* Latitude and altitude\n* Terrestrial biomes\n* Aquatic biomes\n* Plant adaptations\n* Animal adaptations\n* Biodiversity gradients\n* Seasonal patterns\n* Soil and water availability\n* Human impacts", "* Climate shapes vegetation\n* Vegetation shapes habitat structure\n* Species adapt to local conditions\n* Food webs develop within biome constraints\n* Disturbance changes communities\n* Climate change can shift biome boundaries", "* Deforestation\n* Desertification\n* Coral bleaching\n* Wetland loss\n* Protected areas\n* Indigenous stewardship\n* Conservation planning", "Use a global map as the hero with biome panels arranged around it and climate graphs below.", "* Biome boundaries are gradual, not hard lines\n* Do not confuse weather with climate\n* Aquatic biomes depend on salinity, depth, light and flow\n* Avoid treating one biome as more evolved\n* Include human impact without doom-only framing")
add(ECO, "03_Carbon_Cycle_and_Climate.txt", "THE CARBON CYCLE AND CLIMATE", "An illustrated guide to carbon reservoirs, photosynthesis, respiration, oceans, fossil fuels, greenhouse gases and climate change", "* Atmospheric carbon grey\n* Plants green\n* Soil brown\n* Ocean blue\n* Fossil fuels black\n* Emissions orange\n* Carbon storage teal\n* Heat trapping red", "* Atmosphere\n* Carbon dioxide\n* Forest\n* Soil organic carbon\n* Ocean surface\n* Deep ocean\n* Phytoplankton\n* Fossil fuels\n* Volcano\n* Human emissions\n* Carbon sink\n* Greenhouse effect panel", "* Carbon reservoirs\n* Photosynthesis\n* Respiration\n* Decomposition\n* Ocean uptake\n* Sedimentation\n* Fossil fuel combustion\n* Land-use change\n* Greenhouse effect\n* Climate feedbacks\n* Mitigation and adaptation", "* Plants take up carbon dioxide\n* Carbon moves through food webs\n* Respiration returns carbon dioxide\n* Decomposition stores or releases carbon\n* Oceans exchange carbon with atmosphere\n* Fossil fuel burning adds ancient carbon\n* Greenhouse gases trap heat\n* Climate patterns shift", "* Climate change\n* Ocean acidification\n* Forest management\n* Soil carbon\n* Renewable energy\n* Carbon capture concepts\n* Ecosystem protection", "Use a large circular carbon cycle central diagram with natural fluxes and human-added fluxes visually distinguished.", "* Carbon cycle is not only human emissions\n* Human activity has increased atmospheric CO2 substantially\n* Do not show greenhouse effect as a solid glass dome\n* Distinguish carbon storage from permanent removal\n* Avoid unsupported geoengineering claims")
add(ECO, "04_Nitrogen_Cycle.txt", "THE NITROGEN CYCLE", "An illustrated guide to nitrogen fixation, ammonification, nitrification, assimilation, denitrification, fertilizers and ecosystem health", "* Atmospheric nitrogen blue\n* Nitrogen fixation purple\n* Ammonium orange\n* Nitrate green\n* Plants emerald\n* Bacteria teal\n* Fertilizer gold\n* Runoff red", "* Atmospheric N2\n* Nitrogen-fixing bacteria\n* Root nodules\n* Ammonium\n* Nitrifying bacteria\n* Nitrite\n* Nitrate\n* Plant roots\n* Animals\n* Decomposers\n* Denitrifying bacteria\n* Waterway runoff", "* Nitrogen as essential nutrient\n* Nitrogen fixation\n* Ammonification\n* Nitrification\n* Assimilation\n* Denitrification\n* Legume symbiosis\n* Fertilizer use\n* Eutrophication\n* Nitrous oxide emissions", "* Atmospheric nitrogen is fixed\n* Ammonium enters soil\n* Nitrifying bacteria convert ammonium to nitrite and nitrate\n* Plants assimilate nitrate or ammonium\n* Animals obtain nitrogen by eating\n* Decomposers release ammonium\n* Denitrifiers return nitrogen gas to atmosphere", "* Soil fertility\n* Fertilizer management\n* Algal blooms\n* Dead zones\n* Sustainable agriculture\n* Wastewater treatment\n* Climate relevance of nitrous oxide", "Use a soil-plant-water cross-section with nitrogen species arrows and bacteria icons at each transformation.", "* Plants cannot directly use atmospheric N2 without fixation\n* Do not mix up nitrification and denitrification\n* Nitrogen cycle is microbial-driven\n* Fertilizer overuse can harm waterways\n* Keep chemical forms clearly labelled")
add(ECO, "05_Water_Cycle_and_Freshwater_Ecology.txt", "WATER CYCLE AND FRESHWATER ECOLOGY", "An illustrated guide to evaporation, precipitation, groundwater, rivers, lakes, wetlands, watersheds and freshwater life", "* Water blue\n* Clouds white\n* Groundwater cyan\n* Rivers teal\n* Wetlands green\n* Pollution red\n* Aquatic plants emerald\n* Fish silver", "* Ocean\n* Cloud\n* Rain\n* Snow\n* River\n* Lake\n* Wetland\n* Groundwater aquifer\n* Watershed boundary\n* Riparian zone\n* Aquatic plants\n* Macroinvertebrates\n* Fish", "* Evaporation\n* Transpiration\n* Condensation\n* Precipitation\n* Infiltration\n* Runoff\n* Groundwater flow\n* Watersheds\n* Wetland filtration\n* Freshwater food webs\n* Water quality indicators", "* Sun drives evaporation\n* Plants transpire water\n* Clouds form\n* Precipitation falls\n* Water infiltrates soil or runs off\n* Streams connect watersheds\n* Wetlands slow and filter water\n* Rivers deliver water to lakes and oceans", "* Drinking water\n* Flood control\n* Drought\n* Pollution runoff\n* Eutrophication\n* Wetland conservation\n* Freshwater biodiversity loss", "Use a landscape watershed as the central hero with water-cycle arrows and freshwater food-web insets.", "* Groundwater moves slowly, not like underground rivers everywhere\n* Watersheds are land areas draining to a common outlet\n* Wetlands are valuable ecosystems, not wastelands\n* Do not show the water cycle as perfectly closed at local scale\n* Pollution sources should be clearly labelled")
add(ECO, "06_Population_Ecology.txt", "POPULATION ECOLOGY", "An illustrated guide to population growth, carrying capacity, limiting factors, survivorship, age structure and species interactions", "* Population dots blue\n* Births green\n* Deaths red\n* Carrying capacity purple\n* Resources gold\n* Predation orange\n* Competition teal\n* Migration grey", "* Population\n* Habitat\n* Birth rate\n* Death rate\n* Immigration\n* Emigration\n* Exponential curve\n* Logistic curve\n* Carrying capacity line\n* Age pyramid\n* Survivorship curves", "* Population size and density\n* Dispersion patterns\n* Exponential growth\n* Logistic growth\n* Carrying capacity\n* Density-dependent factors\n* Density-independent factors\n* Survivorship types\n* Age structure\n* Metapopulations", "* Births and immigration increase population\n* Deaths and emigration decrease population\n* Resources affect survival and reproduction\n* Rapid growth may slow near carrying capacity\n* Disturbance can reduce population\n* Recovery depends on reproduction and habitat", "* Wildlife management\n* Invasive species\n* Endangered species recovery\n* Fisheries\n* Disease spread\n* Human population concepts\n* Conservation planning", "Use population graphs centrally with a habitat scene and age-structure/survivorship panels below.", "* Carrying capacity can change over time\n* Exponential growth cannot continue forever in finite systems\n* Do not treat population models as exact predictions\n* Distinguish population from community\n* Avoid value judgments about species being good or bad")
add(ECO, "07_Conservation_Biology_and_Biodiversity.txt", "CONSERVATION BIOLOGY AND BIODIVERSITY", "An illustrated guide to genetic, species and ecosystem diversity, extinction risk, habitat protection, restoration and conservation planning", "* Genetic diversity purple\n* Species diversity green\n* Ecosystem diversity blue\n* Threats red\n* Protected areas teal\n* Restoration gold\n* Corridors orange\n* Community action navy", "* DNA diversity icon\n* Species richness panel\n* Ecosystem mosaic\n* Endangered species\n* Habitat fragment\n* Wildlife corridor\n* Protected area\n* Seed bank\n* Restoration site\n* Community conservation", "* Levels of biodiversity\n* Endemism\n* Ecosystem services\n* Extinction drivers\n* Habitat loss and fragmentation\n* Invasive species\n* Overexploitation\n* Pollution\n* Climate change\n* Protected areas\n* Restoration ecology", "* Habitat is assessed\n* Threats are identified\n* Species and genetic diversity are monitored\n* Conservation priorities are set\n* Corridors reconnect habitat\n* Restoration rebuilds ecosystem function\n* Communities and policy support long-term protection", "* IUCN categories concept\n* Captive breeding\n* Rewilding concept\n* Indigenous and local knowledge\n* Urban biodiversity\n* Citizen science\n* Ethical conservation decisions", "Use a biodiversity mosaic centrally with threat arrows on one side and conservation interventions on the other.", "* Biodiversity is more than species count\n* Conservation includes people and ecosystems\n* Avoid presenting captive breeding as universal solution\n* Habitat quality matters, not just area\n* Use respectful language about local communities")
add(ECO, "08_Pollution_and_Biomagnification.txt", "POLLUTION AND BIOMAGNIFICATION", "An illustrated guide to pollutants, bioaccumulation, biomagnification, food webs, health effects and environmental cleanup", "* Pollutants red\n* Water blue\n* Sediment brown\n* Plankton green\n* Small fish silver\n* Large fish orange\n* Top predator purple\n* Cleanup teal", "* Pollution source\n* River or ocean\n* Sediment\n* Plankton\n* Small fish\n* Large fish\n* Bird or human consumer\n* Persistent pollutant molecule\n* Concentration pyramid\n* Cleanup team", "* Pollution types\n* Persistent organic pollutants\n* Heavy metals concept\n* Bioaccumulation\n* Biomagnification\n* Food-web transfer\n* Microplastics overview\n* Eutrophication comparison\n* Monitoring\n* Remediation and prevention", "* Pollutant enters ecosystem\n* Small organisms absorb contaminant\n* Predator eats many contaminated prey\n* Pollutant concentration increases in predator tissues\n* Higher trophic levels may receive larger doses\n* Monitoring detects risk\n* Source reduction prevents future accumulation", "* Mercury in aquatic food webs\n* Pesticide history concept\n* Plastic pollution\n* Industrial runoff\n* Wastewater treatment\n* Environmental justice\n* Food safety advisories", "Use a food chain concentration pyramid as the central visual with pollutant molecules increasing upward.", "* Biomagnification applies strongly to persistent fat-soluble or slowly eliminated substances, not every pollutant\n* Do not confuse bioaccumulation and biomagnification\n* Concentration depends on food web and chemistry\n* Avoid unsupported health claims\n* Prevention at source is key")
